To respond to the first post, the reason no one *accurately* portrays the relationship between Vietnam veterans and the antiwar movement is because the people who continue to send our young men and women off to war need to erase that history.  If young people knew that the antiwar movement during the Vietnam war was actually *pro-GI,* that would raise too many questions about the true effects of antiwar organizations such as ours, Vietnam Veterans Against the War, Inc.  Most young people never heard about the Winter Soldier Investigation or Operation Dewey Canyon III in Washington D.C. in 1971.  The fact that we had nearly 40,000 members during that period, 75% of whom were combat vets doesn't set well with the propaganda about dividing the peace movement from the veterans.<br>
In response to the second post, I'd like to hear more about that Marine who was allegedly killed by an antiwar protestor.  <br>
Sounds to me like one of those apocryphal stories, like the &quot;spitting incidents,&quot; that are used to abracadabra the war into a noble cause and the protestors into evil traitors.  More info, please.
